00:00:10.230 --> 00:00:15.780
GERMAIN: How many people in here have had
an idea for business that they think could

00:00:15.780 --> 00:00:22.370
work? Hands up. Okay. That's pretty good.
And how many people tried to make that idea

00:00:22.370 --> 00:00:27.839
happen? A few hands, two hands. And how many
people made that idea work and it's a roaring

00:00:27.839 --> 00:00:33.320
success now? Two people. That's great. I think
later we'll have great ideas of businesses.

00:00:33.320 --> 00:00:39.510
I think most of them happen on Friday nights
about 9:00 P.M. in pubs with your mates and

00:00:39.510 --> 00:00:45.330
you go, we got to do this thing one day, you
know, maybe. And people talk a good game,

00:00:45.330 --> 00:00:50.809
but rarely get down, to actually start things,
you know, make the idea happen. And I guess

00:00:50.809 --> 00:00:54.750
that's where Innocent got to--Rich, Adam,
and John are the three founders of Innocent.

00:00:54.750 --> 00:00:59.070
I went to university with them. We managed
this since we were 18. And they were always

00:00:59.070 --> 00:01:03.460
the people at the university who were going
to do something, you know, they're always

00:01:03.460 --> 00:01:06.179
doing stuff, you know, basically, in terms
of being quite entrepreneurial in trying to,

00:01:06.179 --> 00:01:14.870
you know, make a quick buck. And I definitely
wasn't really happy, just not being entrepreneurial.

00:01:14.870 --> 00:01:25.620
And obviously, I have changed now in an incredibly
dynamic character. And it's interesting knowing

00:01:25.620 --> 00:01:29.819
them back then, knowing them at about 18 or
so. And about the time we got to about 24,

00:01:29.819 --> 00:01:34.140
when we left university and done a few other
things, they'd been talking about it for so

00:01:34.140 --> 00:01:38.580
long that we should start a business. What
should we do? I don't know, but we should

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:42.979
just have a business. It would be great, wouldn't
it? Wait a minute, why should we have a business?

00:01:42.979 --> 00:01:46.770
Yeah, I said the business, what should it
be? I don't know. They didn't, you know, they

00:01:46.770 --> 00:01:48.759
didn't really know what they were going to
do, but you knew that they were going to do

00:01:48.759 --> 00:01:53.229
something and they just have to get to an
idea, an idea that would work and act on it.

00:01:53.229 --> 00:01:59.550
And Smoothie was, fortunately, for us, the
idea that works in the beginning and still

00:01:59.550 --> 00:02:04.880
works today. Interestingly, the idea--some
of the ideas didn't work. This is one of the

00:02:04.880 --> 00:02:10.259
ideas that didn't work. This is the--can anyone
tell me what that is? Easy, bath, but even

00:02:10.259 --> 00:02:16.480
more--even more specifically? A death trap,
good, is the electric bath, the not-patented

00:02:16.480 --> 00:02:22.159
electric bath. The patent is going if anyone
wants it. I think there's a company in Japan

00:02:22.159 --> 00:02:26.620
called Auto Bath where they actually make
something in this realm. But the idea, the

00:02:26.620 --> 00:02:31.140
idea behind it was great. And again, it was
really, like, 9:00 P.M. Friday night, pop

00:02:31.140 --> 00:02:38.370
up idea, which is... I hate to run baths.
It's pretty boring. What do you do while you're

00:02:38.370 --> 00:02:42.910
waiting? You know, just hanging around especially
with, you know, specifically British plumbing.

00:02:42.910 --> 00:02:46.890
You know, if you ever lived in a flat where
the water comes out, you know, when it takes

00:02:46.890 --> 00:02:53.049
20 minutes to run a bath, that is a real pain
in the bum. So, how can we make this? How

00:02:53.049 --> 00:03:08.159
can we make people's bath experience a better
place? And the only idea was that you could

00:03:08.159 --> 00:03:22.600
kind of automate it. So, getting up in the
morning, let's say 7:15 A.M. and knowing that

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:24.849
your bath has already run to the right depth,
has the correct temperature, has the right

00:03:24.849 --> 00:03:29.420
amount of bubble bath in it, is an amazingly
rewarding experience if only I could have

00:03:29.420 --> 00:03:30.420
that experience. Well, I can't because I don't
have the electric bath. But maybe one day

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:32.099
you can use your electric bath because we're
going to design it and make it and that are--how

00:03:32.099 --> 00:03:34.049
many hotel rooms are in the U.K.? Thousands.
We're going to get the electric bath with

00:03:34.049 --> 00:03:36.379
every one of those. And how many new built
homes were there being built at the end of

00:03:36.379 --> 00:03:39.209
the night? There's thousands, maybe tens of
thousands. We're going to get the electric

00:03:39.209 --> 00:03:41.209
bath into every new home built by [INDISTINCT],
Wimpey, Taylor Woodrow, all those guys are

00:03:41.209 --> 00:03:45.730
going to buy the electric bath. This is a
business with massive potential or death and

00:03:45.730 --> 00:03:49.770
after, you know, after getting quite--seriously
quite excited about it for awhile, always

00:03:49.770 --> 00:03:53.280
realized that when they would ultimately have
to go and sell these ideas to people that

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:56.959
might invest and give them cash to who wins
their business, they were going to have to

00:03:56.959 --> 00:04:05.359
get past this one issue, the death trap issue.
But, you see, I would have been a great investor,

00:04:05.359 --> 00:04:08.579
straight to the point. And so it never actually
made it to business plan phase. Luckily, some

00:04:08.579 --> 00:04:14.510
other ideas, the [INDISTINCT] and... It's
amazing actually because the electric bath

00:04:14.510 --> 00:04:20.570
is our favorite comedy idea that didn't work.
We get sent quite lot of ideas now. People

00:04:20.570 --> 00:04:24.500
are going, oh, you know, Innocent, you seem
like quite a friendly approach with people.

00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:28.560
I have this idea for business and I think
you should make, you know, maybe you could

00:04:28.560 --> 00:04:36.780
help me develop my idea for the cat bag, which
is--it's an amazing device, people have cats

00:04:36.780 --> 00:04:40.970
and cats shed hair. I have a lovely flat and
I love my cat but there's hair everywhere.

00:04:40.970 --> 00:04:45.150
What I'd love is this little, like, boiler
suit bag thing that I can put my cat in, and

00:04:45.150 --> 00:04:51.640
so my flat will be clear and there will be
no hair in the flat. My cat could be happy

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:55.620
and I also support [INDISTINCT] boiler suit
bag thing, without, you know, but without

00:04:55.620 --> 00:05:01.490
that person getting to the second step, which
is a like--what happens when the cat wants

00:05:01.490 --> 00:05:05.930
to go poo. What happens then? I don't want
to be near the bag then. What happens when

00:05:05.930 --> 00:05:10.750
the cat wants to do other stuff, run free?
How you going to take the bag off? But we

00:05:10.750 --> 00:05:15.580
got--we seriously got send out as a business
idea that somebody believed in. The other

00:05:15.580 --> 00:05:20.430
one--and there's a theme here. The other one
was dog nappies. We've been pitched dog nappies

00:05:20.430 --> 00:05:25.640
because one of the scourges of life is the
fact that you spread dog poo in the park,

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:28.550
and wouldn't it be great if dogs just have
little, you know, little nappies they walked

00:05:28.550 --> 00:05:34.060
around in and then you're going to have to,
like, scoop up with a plastic bag and they'll

00:05:34.060 --> 00:05:36.691
[INAUDIBLE]. So you make a couple of ideas
here if you fancy and start your own business,

00:05:36.691 --> 00:05:48.010
cat bag, nappies. I have thought really stupidly.
I pitched three or four ideas to you there

00:05:48.010 --> 00:05:52.900
quite quickly, which is what we were trying
to do back--about 10 years ago. What we realized

00:05:52.900 --> 00:05:57.910
by the end of it in terms of having a great
idea was that we subsequently come up with

00:05:57.910 --> 00:06:03.370
this thing called the Granny Test. In Hollywood
it would be the Elevator Pitch where you are

00:06:03.370 --> 00:06:08.300
an aspiring screenwriter and you've got, you
know, you bump into Steven Spielberg on the

00:06:08.300 --> 00:06:14.630
left and say, right, Spielberg, I've got a
great idea for a movie, it features a cat

00:06:14.630 --> 00:06:20.530
that wears a bag and this dog and a nappy,
is going to be amazing. And you have that,

00:06:20.530 --> 00:06:24.750
you know, you have that 10 seconds to maybe
make your [INDISTINCT] or fall flat in your

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:28.880
face. Our thing is slightly more prosaic because
we know that you're not going to bump in Spielberg

00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:32.140
that often. Also, this is called the Granny
Test because most people got a granny. If

00:06:32.140 --> 00:06:36.111
you don't have a granny, you can borrow somebody
else's granny to [INDISTINCT] around. And

00:06:36.111 --> 00:06:42.900
if you can't explain your business idea in
over a cup of tea with your granny, then it's

00:06:42.900 --> 00:06:47.940
rubbish, then it sucks, because, you know,
your granny sees they're going to--you know,

00:06:47.940 --> 00:06:52.990
if you get, "Oh, that's nice, dear. That's
okay. That's pretty. That might work," if

00:06:52.990 --> 00:06:57.840
you just get a blank look and more tea, then
it's probably--it's probably not going to

00:06:57.840 --> 00:07:02.150
work. Well, I think, in seriousness, testing
out in your friends and your family is the

00:07:02.150 --> 00:07:07.740
only--is the only sure way it's beginning
to work out, that it's going to work. Like

00:07:07.740 --> 00:07:12.880
that whole [INDISTINCT], because I don't--I
want to understand what's going on inside

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:17.630
[INDISTINCT] chap's brains apart from what's
probably not there. Maybe they--they broke

00:07:17.630 --> 00:07:27.020
the mold. Or maybe the grannies were really
clever. So the second law of--or the second

00:07:27.020 --> 00:07:32.140
bit we get to is, so having a great idea is
crucial for every business. I've come to skip

00:07:32.140 --> 00:07:37.080
through it in five minutes with a few funnies,
but actually, you know, it's rare that great

00:07:37.080 --> 00:07:43.020
ideas come. What we've also learned is that
when you think, "I've got a ton of ideas to

00:07:43.020 --> 00:07:46.720
start a business," you start thinking like
an inventor. You start thinking that you've

00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:52.680
got to invent something that nobody has ever
seen before. And, actually, what you tend

00:07:52.680 --> 00:07:57.230
to do is not be an inventor. You tend to just
be an improver or an adapter, just tend to

00:07:57.230 --> 00:08:00.680
make things a bit better. So Smoothie has
all ready existed, right? We just make them

00:08:00.680 --> 00:08:07.560
better, which got better ingredients. We created,
you know, a business and a brand that we think

00:08:07.560 --> 00:08:14.490
sold the idea of Smoothies better to people.
We didn't invent. We're not crazy guys with

00:08:14.490 --> 00:08:21.800
beards hiding in sheds. I have a shed. But
then, when you've had your idea, you got to

00:08:21.800 --> 00:08:27.790
start and that's--arguably, that's even more
difficult than having the idea, because where

00:08:27.790 --> 00:08:36.450
do we start. So where do we buy 10 tons of
mangoes? Who's got--do we need a machine,

00:08:36.450 --> 00:08:41.539
or do we just do it ourselves? Do we just
hire loads of people to chalk it up? What

00:08:41.539 --> 00:08:45.660
about bottles? Where do you get the bottles
from? We have to make those? And then somebody

00:08:45.660 --> 00:08:50.440
is going to get them all in the shops. We
didn't know any of this stuff. We really didn't

00:08:50.440 --> 00:08:55.230
know any of this stuff. And so, the starting
part is the hardest part because you just

00:08:55.230 --> 00:09:01.889
have to start somewhere. You just have to--how
many people in this room have done, say, a

00:09:01.889 --> 00:09:09.970
dissertation or a Ph.D., thesis, or something
in their time in education? How many of you?

00:09:09.970 --> 00:09:15.600
And how many of you started without delaying,
without procrastination, without futzing around,

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:20.420
without drinking coffee, without just not
doing it for quite a lot of time? How many

00:09:20.420 --> 00:09:27.220
of you just started like that? Come on, geeks.
Come on. Somebody did. No, you don't. You

00:09:27.220 --> 00:09:32.100
don't. Even if you kind of know--even if you
kind of know what you're going to do, the

00:09:32.100 --> 00:09:37.550
human race is based on a healthy dose of procrastination,
and it's the same in starting a business.

00:09:37.550 --> 00:09:43.420
You don't really know where and when to start.
I guess in the end, we finally figured out.

00:09:43.420 --> 00:09:47.709
It wasn't about the fact that we didn't know
how to make Smoothies. It was more of the

00:09:47.709 --> 00:09:52.009
point that we didn't really know if anyone
would like them, would like the stuff we were

00:09:52.009 --> 00:09:58.800
